The gameplay is really good, but don't play this if you don't have a big screen and headphones. I'm not scared any more, I'm just angry because I want to beat it very badly. But then the alien starts coming through the vents and even if I can look around really fast and actually see it coming when I press to close the vent NOTHING HAPPENS AND I DIE. Please make this game bearable on smaller devices and without headphones. Having an option to scale the crew command buttons would be so helpful because I can't press hide in time even when I know where the alien is going 5-10 seconds in advance. And just a little visual indicator on where the alien is coming from would be great. Also, I have basically memorized what the alien is going to do every single time. I don't normally tell them to hide because I see the alien is about to enter the room, I tell them to hide because I KNOW the alien is about to enter the room. Every time I restart from the bad controls killing me, the ai does the same thing: - Starts in the same place - Enters the vent - Exits in the same room In my current level, the only reason I'm losing is because I'm getting unlucky on which direction the alien is coming from and the vent doesn't close when I tell it to close.

This is a fun experience that captures the feel of the Alien films, and does so from an angle other games haven't done before. Guiding your crewmembers through the station while trying to keep an eye on the alien is very reminiscent of the vent scene from the first movie. It's tense and exciting, and you feel brilliant when you manage to outsmart the monster and keep your crew safe. It's an enjoyable implementation of the "camera watching" style of horror games, with more control and tactics.

For what this game is it's a fun mobile game using the alien franchise. I have however have seen some minor glitches with the character animations. Personally I am not the biggest fan of this type of game style popularized by the FNAF games but it works here. I also commend this for not relying on in app purchases but as an app for 5$ there should be more content even though $5 is not a huge amount of money but the game is somewhat short. At the end of the day this has a recomendation from me.

Alien: Blackout is a magnificent display and achievement of what's truly capable on mobile. The game takes a fresh approach to mobile game design by utilizing a minimalist control scheme and a strong adherence to open-ended gameplay. The game's goal seems clear-- it's all about 'player choice'. Giving the player numerous choices. This affords the player an array of unique strategies to give a go. Should I take it slow n steady? Or run like hell throw caution to the wind? Maybe Hide like a pansy

As a huge fan of Alien Isolation, I'm so glad this game stayed true to the roots of the original Alien. Excellent game play, performance, concept, voice acting, the list goes on. Very impressed for a mobile game and I hope this developer continues making games as good as this in the Aliens universe!

I do not understand most of the others who rated this game. The story is engaging. I find myself exceedingly frustrated by the limited controls. If I could give a group command, it would make the game much more immersive, but having to tell each character to hide is tedious and unrealistic. The power limitations for a fusion-powered station also make very little sense. Overall apply a neutral rating becuase the designers went for an interesting game, but I personally I see room for improvement.

content: It is a fun tense little game. Unfortunately it too little of a game; as it is over by the time it feels like it really gets started. Don't get me wrong, I enjoyed it, but it feels like only a taste of what the game could be.
